ExtraaLearn Project¶

Context¶

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective¶

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Questions

  1. Leads will have different expectations from the outcome of the course and the current occupation may play a key role in getting them to participate in the program. Find out how current occupation affects lead status.

From my bar graph above that calculates each current occupation to status, we see that people who's current occupation is professional will have a 35% chance of converting. People who's currently unemployed will have a 26% chance of converting. People who's a student will have a 12% chance of converting.

We can conclude that people working have the highest chance of converting to a paying customer.

  1. The company's first impression on the customer must have an impact. Do the first channels of interaction have an impact on the lead status?

From my bar graph that compares the status and first interactions, people who's first interaction with ExtraaLearn was over a website has a 45% chance to convert to a paid customer. People who's first interaction with ExtraaLearn was on the mobile app has a 10% chance to convert to a paid customer.

We can conclude that first channels of interaction has a significant impact on status.

  1. The company uses multiple modes to interact with prospects. Which way of interaction works best?

From my bargraph that compares the modes, website mode worked best with prospects, with around 37% conversion rate.

  1. The company gets leads from various channels such as print media, digital media, referrals, etc. Which of these channels have the highest lead conversion rate?

From my bargraph above that compares all media types and their conversion rates, print_media_type2, or the magazine had the highest conversion rate.

However, I also calculated how many people seen or heard of ExtraaLearn through each media type, and magazine was the lowest. People hear of ExtraaLearn far more than any other media type.

Educational channel reaches the most people. 700 leads say that they had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels.

We can conclude that although magazines have the highest conversion rate, they also reach the least amount of potential leads.

  1. People browsing the website or mobile application are generally required to create a profile by sharing their personal data before they can access additional information.Does having more details about a prospect increase the chances of conversion?

Yes, people who have a high profile completion have roughly a 42% chance of converting to a paying customer, while medium and low have a 19% and 5% chance of converting, respectively.

Outliers

In [29]:
#Use z-scores to find outliers
from scipy import stats
#Find the z-scores for all values in the column
#Find which ones are the outliers and remove

numeric_col = ['age', 'website_visits', 'time_spent_on_website', 'page_views_per_visit' ]
for column in numeric_col:
  z_scores = stats.zscore(data_ohe[column])
  outliers = ((z_scores > 3) | (z_scores < -3))
  data_ohe = data_ohe[~outliers]

print("Data shape after removing outliers:", data_ohe.shape)

Data shape after removing outliers: (4507, 17)

I used z-score to determine the outliers and removed them from data_ohe. We can see that around 100 rows were removed from the data set.

In [35]:
def adj_r2(predictors, targets, predictions):
  r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
  n = predictors.shape[0]
  k = predictors.shape[1]
  return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))

n is the total number of observations

k is the total number of predictors or features

We return the adjusted R squared score because accounts for the complexity of the model by penalizing the addition of unnecessary features.

As the number of features increases, penalty increases

In [36]:
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
  return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions) / targets)) * 100

MAPE measures the accuracy of your model's predictions as a percentage, indicating how far off, on average, the predictions are from the actual values.

In [37]:
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, targets):
  predictions = model.predict(predictors)
  r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
  adj_r2_value = adj_r2(predictors, targets, predictions)
  rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(targets, predictions))
  mae = mean_absolute_error(targets, predictions)

  epsilon = 1e-10  # Small value to avoid division by zero
  targets = np.where(targets == 0, epsilon, targets)  # Replace zero values with epsilon
  mape = np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions) / targets)) * 100

  df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            'RMSE': rmse,
            'R²': [r2],
            'MAE': [mae],
            'MAPE': [mape],
            'Adjusted R²': [adj_r2_value]
        }
    )
  return df_perf

R² (R-Squared): Measures how well the model's predictions explain the variance in the actual target values. A value closer to 1 indicates a better fit.

Adjusted R²: Adjusts the R² score by accounting for the number of predictors in the model, providing a more accurate measure of model performance, especially when multiple features are used.

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): Represents the average prediction error in your model's predictions, expressed in the same units as the target variable. It indicates how far off the predictions are from the actual values on average.

MAE (Mean Absolute Error): The average absolute difference between the model's predictions and the actual target values, providing a straightforward measure of prediction accuracy.

MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error): The average percentage error between the model's predictions and the actual values, indicating how far off predictions are in percentage terms.

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

Unlike a single Decision Tree, Random Forest Regressors inherently reduce overfitting by averaging the results of multiple trees. Instead of pruning, we can tune it.

n_estimators represents the number of decision trees that will be created in the Random Forest ensemble.

You are saying that you want to try the Random Forest with 100, 110, and 120 trees, respectively.

The default value for n_estimators is 100. Including it in your parameter grid ensures that you can compare the performance of the default setting with other values.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Focus on Web Experience:

Time spent on website and First interaction on website are the most influential features. We should improve the website experience by optimizing website content, speed, and user interface to enhance user experience. This can help improve conversion rates.

Encourage Profile Completion:

Since profile completion levels influential features. We can encourage users to complete their profiles. We should implementing reminders to encourage users to fill in missing details, potentially increasing engagement or conversion rates.

Personalize Targeting by Age and Occupation:

Given that age and employment status are significant features, we should personalize marketing campaigns or website experiences based on these demographics. Tailor messages to people in the age range of 40 to 50 years old who are currently working.

Utilize Phone and Website Activities:

Since users' last activities on phones and websites are influential, consider integrating follow-up strategies based on these activities. For example, users who last engaged on their phone might respond well to SMS marketing, while those who engaged via the website could benefit from targeted web ads or emails.

Reevaluate Underperforming Channels:

Since not many people see Extraalearn on magazines and educational_channels, we should consider reducing spending or rethinking strategies for channels since they have minimal impact on the target variable. We can allocate resources to more influential channels.

Optimize Onboarding for Website Interactions

Given that first interaction on website is highly influential, ensure that the onboarding process for website visitors is seamless. This would include engaging landing pages and offering incentives for users who sign up or engage further after their first interaction.

Target Specific Demographic Groups in Marketing Campaigns

Utilize the information from features such as age and current occupation to create targeted marketing campaigns: For younger age groups, use social media platforms like Instagram, TikTok, or Snapchat. For students, promote student discounts or educational resources. For unemployed users, highlight job-related resources, career-building programs, or opportunities to upskill.

Improve the Effectiveness of 'Phone Activity' and 'Website Activity' Channels

Since last activity are important, implement follow-up strategies tailored to these channels: For users whose last activity was via phone, consider sending SMS notifications, reminders, or calls to action. For users whose last activity was through the website, leverage targeted web push notifications or personalized email campaigns.

Analyze Content Performance on Website Pages

Investigate why page views per visit and website visits are influencing factors. This might mean that the quality and relevance of your website content play a role in engagement. Identify high-performing pages and replicate their strategies across the website to improve overall engagement.
